  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
        <div xml:id="KT2-kilavi">
          <p type="edition">iyaṟkaippuṇarcci puṇarntavaḻit talaimakaḷai iyaṟkaippuṇarccikkaṇ iṭaiyīṭupaṭṭu niṉṟa talaimakaṉ, nāṇiṉ nīkkutaḷ poruṭṭu meytoṭṭup payiṟal mutalāyiṉa avaḷmāṭṭu nikaḻttip pāṭuvāṟṟāṟ kūṭiya <app><lem>talaimakaṉatu</lem><rdg wit="#C2">talaimakaṉ taṉatu</rdg></app> aṉpu tōṟṟa nalam pārāṭṭiyatu.</p>
          <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">HE, who found himself  confronted by an obstacle during the natural union with HER, while the natural union was consummated, praising [her] goodness to show the love of HIM who had met [her] by chance(?), working on her at first by trying to touch [her] body to make HER give up shame.</p>
        </div>
        <div xml:id="KT2" corresp="#TNV15poem1">
            <lg type="edition">
<l>                koṅkutēr vāḻkkai yañciṟait tumpi</l>
<l>                kāmañ ceppātu kaṇṭatu moḻimō</l>
<l>                payiliyatu keḻīiya naṭpiṉ mayiliyaṟ</l>
<l>                ceṟiyeyiṟ ṟarivai kūntali</l>
<l>                ṉaṟiyavu muḷavōnī yaṟiyum pūvē.</l>
            </lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>           Pretty-winged bee whose livelihood is searching for pollen<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">koṅku</term> <term xml:lang="ta">tēr</term>: TVG explanation is "to examine [the smells of] pollen" which is much nicer in the given context, because it would relate this otherwise merely adorning attribute to the theme of the poem.</note></l>
<l rend="indent">without saying [what I] desire</l>
<l rend="indent4">speak of what [you've] seen!</l>
<l>           Are the flowers you know also as fragrant</l>
<l rend="indent">as the tresses of the young woman with close set teeth</l>
<l rend="indent">[and] peacock nature, in habitually united intimacy.<note place="foot">This line is really hard in several respects. Neither semantics nor syntax are in any way clear. The traditional solution, is semantically weakly founded and thematically more than improbable. It reads two attributes, one the comparison of woman and peacock where the tertio is supposed to be beauty ("beautiful as a peacock"), the other an Indo-Aryan reinterpretation of the translation given above: "[full] of intimacy that has been united for seven births".</note></l>
            </lg>
        </div>
    </body>
  </text>
